## Architecture rules

- `#![no_std]` in every crate. No `alloc`, no `Vec`, no `String`,
  no `Box`.
- Monomorphisation is the dispatch. No `dyn`, no `TypeId`, no
  `std::any`. WorkUnits are generic over their `AccessSet`; the
  monomorphised function IS the type identity.
- Static composition only. All WUs are registered at compile time
  via the scheduler builder. No `inventory::`, no `#[ctor]`, no
  `#[distributed_slice]`, no runtime plugin discovery. Plan
  parameters adapt; composition does not.
- Pre-allocated thread pool. No `thread::spawn`, `tokio::spawn`,
  `async_std::spawn` at runtime. Threads are spawned once at
  pipeline construction; they park between frames.
- Schedule once, reuse across frames. Plan recompute is rare
  (triggered by structure change). Runtime cost is amortised over
  many frames of reused execution.
- Deterministic morsel assignment. Not work-stealing by default;
  consumers may implement the `Executor` trait for stealing.
- Self-hosting meta pipeline. The scheduler schedules itself via
  meta WUs (`PlanStage → ScheduleReady → PassStart → ScheduleEnd`).
- `hilavitkutin-build` is a build-dep only. It has no runtime deps.
  Its code never links into the consumer's binary.
- `hilavitkutin-api` forbids depending on `hilavitkutin` internals.
  The engine depends on the api, not the other way round.
- `hilavitkutin-ctx`, `-persistence`, `-str` are reusable extensions.
  They do not depend on each other and do not depend on the engine.
- Substrate dependency: the engine consumes `arvo` for numeric and
  analysis primitives (`arvo-graph`, `arvo-bitmask`, `arvo-sparse`,
  `arvo-spectral`, `arvo-comb`). Keep the boundary clean; no
  re-export of arvo types through `hilavitkutin-api`.

## Vocabulary

Authoritative hierarchy (coarsest → finest):

```
pipeline → core → phase ↔ waist → trunk → fiber ↔ branch ↔ bridge
  → morsel → micro-morsel → entry
```

`record` is one data point in a column — never `row`, never
`entity`. A `morsel` windows into a range of records. A `column`
is independent; no tabular joins.

Dead terms (do not introduce; the vocabulary lint scans for these):
`chain`, `chain_group`, `partition`, `archetype`, `entity`, `row`,
`order`. If you need to refer to the engine vocabulary: `chain →
fiber`, `chain_group → trunk`, `partition → phase`, `archetype →
fiber`, `entity/row → record`, `order → scheduling hints`.

## Commit style

Format: `type: lowercase imperative message`. See
`skills/commit-style/SKILL.md`.

Byline policy is configured in `mock/agent/config.toml`
`[attribution]`. The built-in `check-byline.sh` hook enforces it at
